Description: Pterofin is a Houston-based clean technology company developing innovative energy generation devices based on biomimicry
Headquarters Regions: Greater Houston Area, Southern US
Full Description: Pterofin is an innovative approach at creating power using natural wind or water currents based on simple biomimicry; ie, the natural movements displayed by millions of species that have evolved over billions of years.  Pterofin products are controlled by a simple counterbalance system that synchronizes the wings’ position and speed with a mechanical leverage point on the body of the device. The outcome is a coordination of harmonizing the wings pitch angle to a natural frequency of a fluids specific velocity, allowing Pterofin to be extremely efficient at pumping water or generating electricity.  Engineer Carl Baker with PNNL, under the Technical Assistance Program, has confirmed the technology works, saying, ""The design concept is effective in capturing energy from any moving fluid – wind or water... If a kit consisting of a very few simple and inexpensive parts (and some plans or general directions) could be provided to individuals, they could construct a micro-scale generator system using mostly locally-obtained materials. A very small generator system would also provide sufficient power to recharge a cell phone or LED flashlight over the course of a day. Making these devices available to low-income people in developing economies could provide a considerable improvement in quality of life at a very low cost."  Co-inventor and Professor Robert Breidenthal, from the University of Washington College of Engineering explains, "The exploitation of novel physics, like nonsteady effects in aerodynamics, is an attractive approach to develop green energy technologies. The key idea with the nonsteady aerodynamics of wings is that it takes time for a boundary layer to separate. So when you pitch an airfoil up suddenly, the vorticity in the boundary layer takes time to move up away from the surface. As long as it is close to the airfoil surface, the lift coefficient can be very high."  Please visit our website to learn more about our current projects and thanks!

The Solar Water Works Solar PECO system provides stormwater disinfection in a portable, self-contained unit which requires no power or chemical inputs and generates no waste. Users can rate items (one to five stars) from any of 26 categories, including films, websites, actors, books, games, music, drinks, animals, and restaurants. ITOG uses these ratings to recommend items that the user has not rated, allowing discovery of new items based on past preference much as StumbleUpon does. Full Description: Petrosand Energy, Inc. is a Texas exploration and production company, currently focused on the Oil in the Southwest Texas Heavy Oil Providence San Miguel formation and the prolific Eagle Ford shale formation.  The development of unconventional oil reserves has been enhanced with the recent development of new technological approaches.  Petrosand controls 1492 acres in South Texas with the ability to develop heavy oil (API 3.5) from the San Miguel formation and intermediate oil (API 29) from the Eagle Ford shale formation.  The Company has an estimated 145,000,000 barrels of oil in place on it’s two existing leases.    Petrosand entered into agreements with eXoprop and Champ Science and Engineering for the use of their Supramolecular Stimulation Technology for the development of heavy oil in the 1,062,000 acre Southwest Texas Heavy Oil Province with an estimated 10 billion barrels of oil in place.  The company has additionally assembled a team of highly qualified professionals to provide expertise and guidance in the development of the unconventional Eagle Ford shale oil formation.  This is in addition to other formations on the company’s leases indicating a strong potential for petroleum development.

But Jim has $28,000 in student loan debt which he pays $3,600 annually ($300 per month). 30 years from now, Jim may dig his decision but he’ll be dealing with student loan payments for at least the next 10 years.
